VALUES
(42, 23, 18, 43, 18, 39, 40, 'release unto us Barabbas', 'Release of Barabbas', 'Both passages emphasize the crowd''s demand to release Barabbas instead of Jesus. The repetition of the phrase ''release unto us Barabbas'' in both verses highlights this pivotal moment in the trial of Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 18, 43, 19, 15, 16, 'Away with this man', 'Crowd''s Demand for Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the crowd''s demand to crucify Jesus, showcasing their rejection of him in favor of Barabbas. The phrase ''Away with this man'' in Luke parallels the repeated cries in John, illustrating the intensity of the crowd''s desire for Jesus'' execution.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 18, 40, 27, 15, 26, 'release unto us Barabbas', 'Release of Barabbas', 'Both passages emphasize the crowd''s demand for Barabbas'' release over Jesus. This connection highlights the pivotal moment of choice presented to the people, showcasing their preference for Barabbas, which is central to both narratives.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 19, 44, 3, 14, 14, 'for murder', 'Connection of Murderer Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a murderer being favored over an innocent figure. In Luke, the reference to a ''murderer'' connects directly to the denial of ''a murderer'' in Acts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 19, 42, 23, 2, 2, NULL, 'Accusations Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize accusations made against individuals. Luke 23:2 describes accusations against Jesus, while Luke 23:19 refers to a prisoner involved in sedition and murder, highlighting the theme of wrongful charges.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 19, 42, 23, 5, 5, 'sedition made in the city', 'Connection of Sedition and Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of stirring up the people. The sedition mentioned in Luke 23:19 relates to the accusations against Jesus in Luke 23:5, highlighting the tension surrounding his teachings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 20, 41, 15, 15, 15, 'willing to release Jesus', 'Pilate''s Willingness to Release', 'This connection highlights Pilate''s intention to release Jesus in both passages. While Luke emphasizes Pilate''s willingness, Mark shows the outcome of that willingness as he ultimately delivers Jesus to be crucified.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 20, 40, 14, 8, 9, 'willing to release Jesus', 'Influence of Authority and Regret', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority figures grappling with their decisions. In both passages, Pilate and Herod experience regret over their actions, influenced by external pressures. Pilate''s willingness to release Jesus parallels Herod''s sorrow over executing John the Baptist.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 20, 40, 27, 19, 19, 'willing to release Jesus', 'Pilate''s Reluctance and Warning', 'This connection highlights Pilate''s willingness to release Jesus and the warning from his wife about Jesus being ''just.'' Both passages emphasize the tension Pilate faces regarding Jesus'' innocence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 20, 43, 19, 12, 12, 'willing to release Jesus', 'Pilate''s Attempt to Release Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s desire to release Jesus. In Luke, he speaks again to the crowd, while in John, he actively seeks to release him despite opposition from the Jews.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 21, 40, 27, 22, 25, 'Crucify him, crucify him.', 'Call for Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the crowd''s demand to ''crucify him.'' This connection highlights the collective responsibility of the people in the decision to condemn Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 21, 41, 15, 13, 13, 'Crucify him', 'Call for Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the crowd''s demand for Jesus'' crucifixion. The repetition of the phrase ''Crucify him'' in both verses highlights the intensity of this call.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 21, 42, 23, 23, 23, 'Crucify him, crucify him.', 'Crowd''s Demand for Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the crowd''s insistence on crucifying Jesus. The repetition of ''crucify him'' in the source verse connects directly to the crowd''s loud voices demanding his crucifixion in the target passage.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 21, 43, 19, 15, 15, 'Crucify him, crucify him.', 'Crowd''s Demand for Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the crowd''s demand for Jesus'' crucifixion. The repetition of the phrase ''crucify him'' in both verses highlights the intensity of their call for his execution.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 22, 42, 23, 14, 14, NULL, 'Judgment of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of fault found in Jesus. In Luke 23:14, Pilate states he has found no fault, and in Luke 23:22, he reiterates that he has found no cause of death in him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 22, 42, 23, 16, 16, NULL, 'Chastisement and Release Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''I will therefore chastise him, and release him,'' indicating a direct link in the narrative regarding the treatment of Jesus. This connection highlights the decision to punish without cause and the intention to ultimately set him free.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 22, 42, 23, 20, 20, NULL, 'Pilate''s Intent to Release Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s desire to release Jesus. In Luke 23:20, Pilate speaks again to the crowd with the intention of freeing him, while in Luke 23:22, he expresses that he finds no cause for death and plans to chastise him instead.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 22, 60, 1, 19, 19, 'no cause of death in him', 'Connection of Innocence and Sacrifice', 'This connection highlights the theme of innocence, as both passages refer to a figure without blemish or cause for death. In Luke, the emphasis is on the lack of evil found in Jesus, while 1 Peter describes Him as a lamb without blemish.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 22, 60, 3, 18, 18, 'no cause of death in him', 'Suffering and Innocence Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for the unjust. In Luke, the declaration of no evil emphasizes Christ''s innocence, while 1 Peter speaks of Christ suffering for sins despite being just.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 23, 38, 11, 8, 8, NULL, 'Rejection of Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection of authority. In Luke, the crowd demands crucifixion, paralleling Zechariah''s mention of cutting off shepherds, indicating a disdain for leadership.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 23, 19, 57, 4, 4, 'the voices of them and of the chief priests prevailed', 'Theme of Persecution and Danger', 'Both passages emphasize the danger faced by the innocent. In Luke, the crowd''s loud voices demand crucifixion, while in Psalms, the speaker describes being among lions and facing sharp weapons, symbolizing hostility.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 23, 19, 22, 12, 13, 'the voices of them and of the chief priests prevailed', 'Connection of Opposition and Violence', 'This connection highlights the theme of opposition faced by the innocent. Both passages emphasize the aggressive and overwhelming nature of those who oppose, as seen in the ''loud voices'' demanding crucifixion and the ''strong bulls'' besieging the speaker.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 23, 42, 23, 5, 5, NULL, 'Public Outcry Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the intense public demand for Jesus'' crucifixion and the accusations against him. The loud voices in the first passage reflect the fierce claims in the second about Jesus stirring up the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 24, 40, 27, 26, 26, 'gave sentence that it should be', 'Pilate''s Sentence and Barabbas', 'This connection highlights Pilate''s role in the decision-making process regarding Jesus'' fate. Both passages emphasize Pilate''s actions leading to Jesus'' crucifixion.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 24, 2, 23, 2, 2, 'gave sentence that it should be', 'Judgment and Following the Crowd', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment influenced by the crowd. In Luke, Pilate''s decision reflects the pressure of the multitude, paralleling Exodus''s warning against following many to do evil.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 24, 20, 17, 15, 15, 'it should be as they required', 'Justice and Injustice in Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of unjust judgment, as Pilate''s sentence reflects the act of justifying the wicked. Proverbs 17:15 condemns those who justify the wicked, emphasizing the moral implications of such actions.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 24, 41, 15, 15, 15, 'as they required', 'Pilate''s Decision to Please the Crowd', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s decision to satisfy the people''s demands. In Luke, Pilate''s sentence aligns with the desire of the crowd, while Mark highlights his willingness to content the people by releasing Barabbas.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 24, 43, 19, 1, 1, 'Pilate gave sentence that it should be as they required', 'Pilate''s Judgment and Actions', 'This connection highlights Pilate''s role in the trial of Jesus. The sentence given by Pilate in Luke leads directly to the action of scourging in John, illustrating the consequences of his judgment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 25, 44, 3, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Denial and Murderer', 'Both passages emphasize the choice to release a murderer instead of Jesus. The phrase ''desired a murderer'' in Acts directly parallels the ''him that for sedition and murder'' in Luke, highlighting the rejection of the Holy One.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 25, 41, 15, 6, 7, 'whom they had desired', 'Connection of Barabbas and Insurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the release of a prisoner during the feast, specifically mentioning Barabbas, who was involved in insurrection and murder. This connection highlights the choice between Barabbas and Jesus, illustrating the theme of justice and public desire.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
